<article>
    <h1>Geron&#xAD;toc&#xAD;racy rules</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201107/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-07"><time>2020-11-07</time></a>
        - <span>ASIAN INSIDER</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>M. Tau­fiqur­rah­man</p>
    <p>The Jakarta Post, In­done­sia</p>
    <p>Who­ever wins the US pres­i­den­tial elec­tion, ei­ther Mr Joe Bi­den or Mr Don­ald Trump will set a new record as the old­est per­son to be sworn in as pres­i­dent on Jan 20.</p>
    <p>At 78 years old, Mr Bi­den would be the old­est per­son to be in­au­gu­rated as US pres­i­dent in a first term, while Mr Trump, 74, would be the old­est politi­cian to be sworn in for a sec­ond term.</p>
    <p>Democ­racy in Amer­ica may be the old­est in the world, but the coun­try’s pop­u­la­tion is rel­a­tively young and that should have been re­flected in the make-up of its rul­ing class. Last year, mil­len­ni­als, those aged be­tween 23 and 38, out­num­bered baby boomers. Yet, those 73 mil­lion mil­len­ni­als failed to bring younger politi­cians like Mr Pete But­tigieg or Mr An­drew Yang to the fin­ish line in the pres­i­den­tial pri­maries.</p>
    <p>It ap­pears that geron­toc­racy, gov­ern­ment based on rule by old peo­ple, has be­come a fact of life in the US, and in a large part of our world.</p>
    <p>But be­fore we dis­miss this lurch to­wards geron­toc­racy, we should be re­al­is­tic enough to see that in times of great trans­for­ma­tion like to­day, maybe, just maybe, tap­ping these wheez­ing geezers to lead is the best op­tion.</p>
    <p>What older politi­cians lack in ide­al­ism they can make up for in ex­pe­ri­ence and, hope­fully, wis­dom (Mr Joe Bi­den ap­pears to have much of it).</p>


</article>

